    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Shield of Their Own</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Albert L Weeks letter debunks Chinese and Russian objections to US antimissile defense</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Chinese and Russian objections to an American antimissile defense (front page, May 11) make no sense.</p>
        <p>Why don't these countries build their own antimissile defense? Is the United States the only country that is a potential missile threat to them? In China's case, India represents a tangible potential threat.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Chinese and Russian objections to an American antimissile defense (front page, May 11) make no sense.</p>
        <p>Why don't these countries build their own antimissile defense? Is the United States the only country that is a potential missile threat to them? In China's case, India represents a tangible potential threat.</p>
        <p>I fail to understand these unwarranted objections when national missile defense is a defensive system, not an offensive one. Several countries, if they built such defenses, would save themselves expenditures on offensive systems.</p>
        <p>ALBERT L. WEEKS  Sarasota, Fla., May 11, 2000</p>
      </block>
